* Today's Capabilities of Neural Interfaces

Thought-controlled prosthetic limb with sensory feedback.

.image inc/prosthesis.jpg 320 480

* Thought-Control of a Rat's Tail

An experiment was conducted at Harvard last year in which a human was able to control the movement of a rat's tail by thoughts alone.

Through a brain-computer interface (EEG in this case) the thoughts _up_ and _down_ were read from the human brain. These commands where transferred through a computer-brain interface (HIFU in this case) to specific areas of the rat's brain which control motor activity.

Neither the human nor the rat required any surgery for the experiment.

* Direct Brain-to-Brain Communication in Humans

In a similar experiment conducted at the University of Washington researchers have showcased a non-invasive human-to-human brain interface, using EEG for input and TMS for output. In the experiment TMS was used to stimulate the left motor cortex, which controls hand movements, effectively causing the test subject to involuntarily move his right index finger.

.link https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rNRDc714W5I#t=65 Direct Brain-to-Brain Communication in Humans: A Pilot Study

* Bionic Eyes

Bionic eyes encode visual stimuli and send it directly to the brain through the optic nerve. Similar to that of video encoding, only the difference between frames (moments in time) is transferred. Thus less information is required to be sent, and the brain can more easily adapt to changes in the environment.

.image inc/bionic_eye.jpg 250 453

* Visualizing Thoughts

In an experiment test subjects were shown hundreds of hours of YouTube footage while their brain activity was recorded using fMRI (functional magnetic resonance imaging). This data was later used to reconstruct images from brain activity.

.image inc/minds_eye.png 300 542

.link https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SjbSEjOJL3U#t=255 Mary Lou Jepsen on imaging the mind's eye (watch the talk on YouTube)

